What is AOP?
AOP stands for Aspect-Oriented Programming. It is a programming paradigm that separates cross-cutting concerns from your actual business logic.
A cross-cutting concern is any logic that repeats across many classes and has nothing to do with the core business —
    logging, security, transaction management, auditing, performance monitoring, caching, exception handling. Without AOP you scatter this code everywhere. 
With AOP you write it once and apply it anywhere declaratively.

WITHOUT AOP — cross-cutting concern scattered everywhere
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  OrderService.java
  ─────────────────
  public void placeOrder(Order order) {
      log.info("Entering placeOrder");          // logging
      checkPermission("ROLE_USER");             // security
      long start = System.currentTimeMillis();  // performance
      try {
          // actual business logic — 5 lines
          validateOrder(order);
          inventory.reserve(order);
          payment.charge(order);
      } catch (Exception e) {
          log.error("placeOrder failed", e);    // exception
          throw e;
      } finally {
          log.info("Time: " + (System.currentTimeMillis()-start));
      }
  }

  CustomerService.java — same boilerplate repeated
  PaymentService.java  — same boilerplate repeated
  InventoryService.java— same boilerplate repeated

  PROBLEMS:
  → Business logic buried inside infrastructure code
  → Any change to logging format = edit 50 files
  → Impossible to unit test business logic in isolation
  → Violates Single Responsibility Principle


WITH AOP — business logic stays clean
──────────────────────────────────────
  OrderService.java
  ─────────────────
  public void placeOrder(Order order) {
      validateOrder(order);       // pure business logic only
      inventory.reserve(order);
      payment.charge(order);
  }

  LoggingAspect.java      → handles logging for ALL services
  SecurityAspect.java     → handles auth checks for ALL services
  PerformanceAspect.java  → handles timing for ALL services

  Change logging format → edit ONE file → applies everywhere

  Core AOP Terminology:
  ASPECT
  ───────
  The class that contains your cross-cutting logic.
  Example: LoggingAspect, SecurityAspect, AuditAspect
  Annotated with @Aspect + @Component

  JOIN POINT
  ───────────
  Any point in program execution where an Aspect CAN be applied.
  In Spring AOP, a join point is always a METHOD EXECUTION.
  Every method call in a Spring bean is a potential join point.

  POINTCUT
  ─────────
  The expression that SELECTS which join points to intercept.
  Think of it as a filter / query over all join points.
  Example: "intercept all methods in package com.app.service"

  ADVICE
  ───────
  The actual code that runs at a matched join point.
  There are 5 types — see below.

  WEAVING
  ────────
  The process of linking Aspects with the target objects.
  Spring AOP does weaving at RUNTIME using proxies.
  AspectJ does it at compile time or load time (more powerful).

  TARGET OBJECT
  ──────────────
  The original bean whose method is being intercepted.
  Spring wraps this in a PROXY — the caller never knows.

  PROXY
  ──────
  The wrapper Spring creates around your bean.
  All calls go through the proxy first, then to the real bean.
  Two types: JDK Dynamic Proxy (interface-based)
             CGLIB Proxy (subclass-based, no interface needed)

  The 5 Types of Advice
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        5 ADVICE TYPES                                   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  1. @Before
  ───────────
  Runs BEFORE the target method executes.
  Cannot stop the method from running (unless it throws exception).
  Use for: security checks, input validation, logging entry

  @Before("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
  public void logBefore(JoinPoint jp) {
      log.info("Calling: " + jp.getSignature().getName());
  }


  2. @After (finally)
  ────────────────────
  Runs AFTER the method, whether it succeeded or threw exception.
  Like a finally block.
  Use for: releasing resources, cleanup

  @After("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
  public void afterMethod(JoinPoint jp) {
      log.info("Completed: " + jp.getSignature().getName());
  }


  3. @AfterReturning
  ───────────────────
  Runs ONLY when method returns successfully (no exception).
  Can access the return value.
  Use for: audit logging successful operations, caching results

  @AfterReturning(
      pointcut = "execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))",
      returning = "result"
  )
  public void afterSuccess(JoinPoint jp, Object result) {
      log.info("Returned: " + result);
  }


  4. @AfterThrowing
  ──────────────────
  Runs ONLY when method throws an exception.
  Can access the exception object.
  Use for: error logging, alerting, exception translation

  @AfterThrowing(
      pointcut = "execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))",
      throwing = "ex"
  )
  public void afterException(JoinPoint jp, Exception ex) {
      log.error("Exception in " + jp.getSignature() + ": " + ex.getMessage());
  }


  5. @Around  ← most powerful, most commonly used
  ─────────────
  Wraps the entire method. YOU control whether the method runs.
  Can modify args before, modify return value after.
  Must call proceed() to invoke the actual method.
  Use for: performance timing, caching, transaction management,
           rate limiting, circuit breaking

  @Around("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
  public Object around(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp) throws Throwable {
      long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
      try {
          Object result = pjp.proceed();  // ← call actual method
          return result;
      } finally {
          long time = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
          log.info("Took: " + time + "ms");
      }
  }

Pointcut Expression Syntax:

  ANATOMY OF execution() EXPRESSION
  ────────────────────────────────────
  execution( [modifier] returnType [declaring-type] method(params) )

       execution(  *          com.app.service.*    .  *   (..))
                   │          │                       │    │
                   │          │                       │    └── any params
                   │          │                       └── any method name
                   │          └── any class in service package
                   └── any return type


  COMMON PATTERNS
  ────────────────
  All methods in a class:
  execution(* com.app.service.OrderService.*(..))

  All methods in a package:
  execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))

  All methods in package and sub-packages:
  execution(* com.app..*.*(..))

  Only public methods:
  execution(public * com.app..*.*(..))

  Methods returning String:
  execution(String com.app..*.*(..))

  Methods with specific param type:
  execution(* com.app..*.*(com.app.model.Order, ..))

  Methods annotated with custom annotation:
  @annotation(com.app.annotation.Loggable)

  All methods in beans annotated with @Service:
  @within(org.springframework.stereotype.Service)


  COMBINING POINTCUTS
  ────────────────────
  @Pointcut("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
  public void serviceLayer() {}

  @Pointcut("execution(* com.app.repository.*.*(..))")
  public void repositoryLayer() {}

  @Before("serviceLayer() || repositoryLayer()")  // OR
  @Before("serviceLayer() && repositoryLayer()")  // AND (rare)
  @Before("serviceLayer() && !repositoryLayer()") // NOT

  How Spring AOP Works Internally — Proxy Flow:
  APPLICATION STARTUP
  ────────────────────
  Spring Container starts
        │
        ▼
  Scans for @Aspect classes
        │
        ▼
  For each bean that matches any Pointcut expression:
        │
        ▼
  Wraps that bean in a PROXY (JDK or CGLIB)
        │
        ▼
  Registers the PROXY in context instead of real bean
        │
        ▼
  Application ready — callers get the proxy, not the real bean


  RUNTIME METHOD CALL FLOW
  ─────────────────────────
  Caller
    │
    │ calls orderService.placeOrder(order)
    ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                PROXY (invisible to caller)          │
  │                                                     │
  │  1. Intercept the call                              │
  │  2. Build MethodInvocation chain                    │
  │  3. Execute @Before advice(s)                       │
  │  4. Execute @Around advice (before proceed())       │
  │  5. ──────► call real method on target bean ◄────── │
  │  6. Execute @Around advice (after proceed())        │
  │  7. Execute @AfterReturning OR @AfterThrowing       │
  │  8. Execute @After advice                           │
  │  9. Return result to caller                         │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
    │
    ▼
  Caller receives result


  JDK PROXY vs CGLIB PROXY
  ──────────────────────────
  JDK Dynamic Proxy
  ─────────────────
  Bean implements an interface → Spring uses JDK proxy
  Proxy implements same interface as bean
  Caller must use interface type (not concrete class)

  OrderService (interface)
       ▲
       │ implements
  OrderServiceImpl (real bean)
       │
       │ wrapped by
  $Proxy23 (JDK proxy) ← what Spring puts in context


  CGLIB Proxy
  ────────────
  Bean has NO interface → Spring uses CGLIB
  CGLIB creates a subclass of your bean at runtime
  Proxy IS a subclass → no interface needed

  OrderService (concrete class)
       │
       │ subclassed by
  OrderService$$EnhancerByCGLIB (CGLIB proxy)


  ⚠ SELF-INVOCATION PROBLEM
  ───────────────────────────
  class OrderService {
      public void placeOrder() {
          this.validateOrder();  // ← AOP will NOT intercept this
      }
      public void validateOrder() { ... }
  }

  When a method calls another method on ITSELF (this.),
  it bypasses the proxy — AOP advice does NOT fire.

  FIX: Inject self as a bean, or restructure into separate classes
  @Autowired private OrderService self;
  self.validateOrder();  // ← goes through proxy → AOP fires

